The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton —— This summer, readers around the world celebrated the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series —— Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the United States) at literary festivals and bookstores. They had good reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard made his debut on June 26, 1997, this "Boy Who Lived" has become a "symbol of resilience and perseverance."
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven books, been translated into more than 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight films based on the book have grossed a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard to imagine a day when global audiences are not captivated by Rowling's works for people of a certain age and with a literary mindset.
Therefore, I am still astonished every time I recall my students' poor reaction to "Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone" in the fall of 1999, when I included this work in the syllabus of my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching the "Bestselling American Books" series course since 1993.
The course studies popular works from the 17th century up to the present, inviting students to think about why and in what ways these bestsellers have attracted their audiences.
At the end of each semester, I ask my students to select a final work that represents popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first "Harry Potter" novel.
That year, the Potter fever fiercely hit the American coast.
In June, the American publisher of this series urgently pushed the hardcover edition of the second book in the Harry Potter series, "Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets," into bookstores.
The institution also published the third book of this series, "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban," on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone."
By the end of that month, Rowling's novels had occupied the top three spots on The New York Times bestseller list, and the paperback edition of "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" had topped the paperback book sales chart.
Time magazine even printed this glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
Harry Potter's image is everywhere in sight.
My students were eager to know why such a frenzy had occurred.
My goodness, they were extremely disappointed.
In their view, the Harry Potter series is nothing more than second-rate nonsense, which cannot compare with the works such as The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings that they cherished in their childhood memories.
Although their childhood had just passed a few years ago, they accused Harry Potter, just like many notorious adult critics, of being "fabricated", "poorly written", "clichéd", and "boring".

In their view, Harry had neither miracles nor wit nor warmth.
The students' resentment surprised me, but in hindsight, there was nothing really remarkable about it.
Although adults had always formed a significant part of the audience for Harry Potter, these students were precisely at the wrong age to objectively understand the phenomenon of Harry Potter.
They had passed the age of accepting new children's books, but at the same time were too young to have their own children (at that time I had just had my own child), and they eagerly insisted that although the Harry series was now popular, it would soon be forgotten by people.
In the fall of the following year, that is, 2000, the next batch of students also chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone" as their final analysis text, just like their predecessors, they confidently rejected this work.
Let's fast forward to spring 2007.
After setting the course aside for several years, I taught "Bestselling American Books" again.
When students selected their final analysis text, they chose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone".
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This is a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who first read Rowling's works when they were not university students but just teenagers, at the beginning of adolescence. This means they grew up together with Harry, Ron, and Hermione as youths.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" has become a motto rather than a label.
Could Harry disappear from memory?
It is impossible as long as we are alive.
Since 2010, I have taught a best-selling course twice, and both times the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final reviews.
Is it because people are tired of Potter?
Based on the reviews of the Harry Potter series from another course I taught on children's literature, this seems unlikely.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," instead I chose "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban"—this is my favorite among the seven Harry Potter novels, marking the series' transition from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book the most.
But how long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I first conduct a poll: "Which books from the syllabus did you read during your childhood?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban.
In 2012, this figure rose to 94%.
But in the following years, the percentage continued to decline —— 87% in 2014, and dropping to 81% in 2016.
These are not sciences, I know.
But I'm curious: next spring, when I teach "Children's Literature" again, will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80%?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that the status of Harry Potter is continuously declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead, where the percentage can stabilize and stop declining?
Maybe Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I'm happy to have him in my class all along.
